{"cursor":"11373","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Right ascension' (abbreviated 'RA'; symbol 'Î±') is the astronomical term for\none of the two direction coordinates of a point on the celestial sphere in the\nequatorial coordinate system, usually combined with declination. Right\nascension's angular distance is measured eastward along the celestial equator\nfrom the vernal equinox to the hour circle of the point in question.\n{{cite book\n | author = U.S. Naval Observatory Nautical Almanac Office editor = Seidelmann,\n | P. Kenneth title = Explanatory Supplement to the Astronomical Almanac\n | publisher = University Science Books, Mill Valley, CA year = 1992\n |page=735\n | isbn = 0-935702-68-7}}\n\n[[File:Ra and dec demo animation small.gif|right|thumb|350px| 'Right ascension'\nand declination as seen on the inside of the celestial sphere. The primary\ndirection of the system is the vernal equinox, the ascending node of the\necliptic (red) on the celestial equator (blue). Right ascension is measured\neastward along the celestial equator from the primary direction.]]\n\nAn old term, right ascension (Latin, ascensio recta {{cite book\n|url=http://books.google.com/?id=vi4PAAAAQAAJ |title=Institutio Astronomica\n|year=1668 |first=Guilielmi |last=Bleau |page=65 }}, at\n[http://books.google.com/books Google books], \"Ascensio recta Solis, stellÃ¦, aut\nalterius cujusdam signi, est gradus Ã¦quatorus cum quo simul exoritur in sphÃ¦ra\nrecta\"; roughly translated, \"Right ascension of the Sun, stars, or any other\nsign, is the degree of the equator which rises together in a right\nsphere\" ) refers to the ascension, or the point on the celestial equator\nwhich rises with any celestial object, as seen from the Earth's equator, where\nthe celestial equator intersects the horizon at a right angle. It is contrasted\nwith oblique ascension, the point on the celestial equator which rises with a\ncelestial object as seen from almost anywhere else on Earth, where the celestial\nequator intersects the horizon at an oblique angle. {{cite book\n|url=http://books.google.com/?id=Z1QmAAAAMAAJ |title=A Compendious Treatise on\nthe Use of Globes and Maps |year=1821 |first=John |last=Lathrop |publisher=Wells\nand Lilly and J.W. Burditt, Boston |pages=29, 39 }}, at\n[http://books.google.com/books Google books]\n","linknr":280,"url":"Right_ascension","recorded":1375089406,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Right_ascension&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Right_ascension&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Astronomical","/wiki/Coordinate","/wiki/Celestial_sphere","/wiki/Equatorial_coordinate_system","/wiki/Declination","/wiki/Celestial_equator","/wiki/Equinox","/wiki/Hour_circle","#cite_note-1","/wiki/File:Ra_and_dec_demo_animation_small.gif","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/66/Ra_and_dec_demo_animation_small.gif","/wiki/File:Ra_and_dec_demo_animation_small.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Declination","/wiki/Celestial_sphere","/wiki/Equinox","/wiki/Ecliptic","/wiki/Celestial_equator","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Celestial_equator","/wiki/Earth","/wiki/Equator","/wiki/Celestial_equator","/wiki/Horizon","/wik